<div class="story">

<h2>The Laurel Glass</h2>

<p>
This glass was made for Jennifer Caudipteryx when she was elevated to the Order of the Laurel.  
When I wrote the post, I told her something that was very true: I wouldn't have gotten through some difficult parts of my life without her support. When I had to rehome my cats and was dealing with a lot emotionally, she was there.
</p>

<p>
But beyond that, she represents what it means to be a peer. Her dedication to art and the people around her is incredible. Making this glass felt like the smallest way I could say thank you for being part of my life.
</p>

</div>


<div class="story">

<h2>Esme's Vigil Glass</h2>

<p>
When I heard Candace Musmeci — Esme Bramley — was being placed on vigil, I jumped on the opportunity to make a glass for her. Someone jokingly told me “If you love Esme, come to Ymir,” and that was enough motivation for me.
</p>

<p>
Years earlier I had gone to Ymir and stayed in a cabin with people I had never met. Esme was one of the people who made that weekend unforgettable. She has always been someone I could talk to when I was frustrated and someone who celebrated with me when things went well.
</p>

<p>
She’s also the friend I tag in glamour photos because of a running joke she once made. That kind of humor and kindness is exactly who she is. I didn’t need to tell her to “be the peer a newcomer needs to see.” She already was.
</p>

</div>


<div class="story">

<h2>The First Song Scroll</h2>

<p>
I had talked about wanting to create a scroll for a long time. Eventually I decided to stop waiting and just try it.
</p>

<p>
I partnered with Adela Scrijver van Brugge and Tom Saucer. Tom wanted to write the text and I wanted to engrave the artwork on glass. When we looked through potential recipients, I saw a name I had known since I was young and immediately asked if I could take that one.
</p>

<p>
My first attempt broke because I used a cheap frame and applied too much pressure. Later I switched to a better piece of glass but ran into another issue when my engraving bit started to wear down. Even with the mistakes, I loved the result.
</p>

<p>
It was my first time creating a full scroll piece rather than just engraving names or small designs. When people heard I had made a scroll they assumed I meant calligraphy. When they realized it was glass they said, “Oh. That means it’s a Song Scroll.”
</p>

</div>


<div class="story">

<h2>The Rodney Glass</h2>

<p>
This glass was one of the most emotional pieces I've ever made.
</p>

<p>
It was a gift celebrating the knighting of a friend. When I told David Stewart he might cry when he saw it, he said he wouldn’t. He didn’t — but the moment was still powerful.
</p>

<p>
The glass was given from me and Rodney Woods. Rodney meant a lot to both of us and capturing this moment in glass felt like preserving something important in time.
</p>

</div>


<div class="story">

<h2>Elevation Gifts</h2>

<p>
One of my favorite things about making art in the SCA is creating gifts for people’s elevations. Every one of these pieces represents a story and a relationship.
</p>

<p>
For Carson Reed I created a mug celebrating his elevation to the Order of the Mark. Carson is one of the people who pushed me to organize my first interkingdom practice — which eventually grew into what is now known as Borders Without Walls.
</p>

<p>
For Adela Scrijver van Brugge I made a pelican-themed pitcher. It broke during travel but she immediately said she could repair it with epoxy and gold, seeing beauty in the broken piece.
</p>

<p>
That moment perfectly summed up why she deserved the Pelican.
</p>

</div>


<div class="story">

<h2>Stained Glass Experiments</h2>

<p>
Not all of my projects are engraving. Sometimes I experiment with other materials like stained glass.
</p>

<p>
These pieces were made as gifts from the Shire of Nantyderwyddon to the Crown. They combine heraldry with glasswork and let me explore color in ways engraving cannot.
</p>

